[{"id":"VH986015","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH948463.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The speaker’s use of imagery when describing the corn vines in lines 4 and 5 appeals to both</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH986015_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<p class=\"lead_in\"><span class=\"compose_cluster_phrase type:ordinal\"></span> Read the following poem carefully before you choose your answers.</p>\n\n<p class=\"introduction passage-intro\">This poem is from a collection published in 2008.</p>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"poetry style:1\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Pumpkin Farm, Half Moon Bay</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"verse\"><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">1&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Now you veer away from me like a sailor on his keel</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>into a windless place, into gold corn blades coiling</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>in the dry light-and-shade of furrows run over everywhere</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>with vines, brown curls rasping like metal files</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">5&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>against the cotton weave of your sweatshirt.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>You enter the rows shoulder first, sideways.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>A note I make of your character: that instinct</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>to minimize destruction, whistling the scalpel’s</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>shining lyric all the way into a dark veiny passage,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">10&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>stitching the wound to stop the pain.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Meanwhile a crowd of schoolchildren out of school</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>managed only loosely by their teachers</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>are bruising the natural world, their voices</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>high-pitched confusions of sea birds. Clumps</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">15&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>of little boys and girls climbing blocks of hay,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>piles of pumpkins, the big green tractor.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>They are everywhere, a scramble of jostlings</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and tumblings, the flinging of arms as they jump,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the pumping of fists into shoulders. I know</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">20&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the changing expressions of the faces</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and what is likely to happen next: boys lift</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>pumpkins the size of basketballs over their heads,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>trying to smash them, wanting to see them explode.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>You turn back to say something I’m too far away to hear.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">25&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>The trouble with me is I worry too much about intrusion,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and imagine too purely someone else’s passions</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and get them wrong. Some days everything seems</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>pointless. What moves any of us to do what we do?</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>I go around the field of corn on a rutted</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">30&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>tractor road, pushing a barrow of pumpkins to the car.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>And you? Whatever you’ve said is over.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>You’re seeing between the rows the same unruly</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>mess of tissues, organs, shapes</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>such as those you’ve learned to cut into,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">35&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>cutting like Aeneas<span class=\"footnote\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"footnote_mark\">1</span><span class=\"footnote_text\">In Greco-Roman mythology, and as seen in the epic poem by Virgil, Aeneas was a Trojan hero who sailed the Mediterranean to Rome after the Trojan War.</span></span> through waves blown red and black</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>by a cold wind, one city or another at his back</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>burning, and nothing in the way of his future.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>In the offing there is nothing but blue, water and sky—</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the straight, the narrow, the exact.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">40&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>In your mind you’re rehearsing some procedure—</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the yards, the riggings, the sutures yare in your hands.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>This, like this. Yes, yes. This. You’re seeing</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>what in the body is in the way, occlusions and clamps</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and the new sealing knife that burns the bleeders shut.</span></div>\n<span class=\"mandatory_credit_block\"><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">Used by permission.</span></span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">touch and smell</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">smell and hearing</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">hearing and sight</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">taste and hearing</p>"],"answer":2}]